fields.name: Naked Mole Rat
fields.description: Naked mole-rats, as their name suggests, are pink, nearly hairless subterranean rodents. These surprisingly long-lived animals are one of the only true eusocial mammals and live in underground burrows in eastern Africa.
fields.fact: A naked mole-rat can move each of its front teeth separately, like a pair of chopsticks. They also eat their own poo!

fields.name: Blue Gaucus
fields.description: Also known as the Blue Dragon, Sea Swallow or Blue Angel, the Blue Glaucus is a species of brightly colored sea slug (nudibranch), and can be found throughout the Atlantic, Pacific and Indian Oceans in temperate and tropical waters. Like most nudibranchs, this species incorporates toxic chemicals or stinging cells from its prey into its own skin. This ability provides the Blue Glaucus with a defense mechanism against predation.
fields.fact: This animal's blue color is for more than just show. The sea slug uses its hue to its advantage as it floats on the ocean's surface. Its cyanic side faces upward to camouflage it against the sea's blue color, while the silver side faces downward to camouflage it against the water's bright surface.

fields.name: Star Nosed Mole
fields.description:
A star-nosed mole is surely one of the world's weirdest-looking animals. If you were to come face to face with one, you might think its head had been replaced by a tiny octopus.

And for an animal that’s nearly blind, the American species is astonishingly speedy: The world’s fastest eater, it can find and gobble down an insect or worm in a quarter of a second.
fields.fact: One of two animals in the world known to smell underwater, by blowing air bubbles and sucking them back into its nose.

fields.name: Axolotl
fields.description: As legend has it, the axolotl is the Aztec god of fire and lightning, Xolotl, which disguised himself as a salamander to avoid being sacrificed. But these Mexican amphibians are impressive enough on their own, with the ability to regenerate lost limbs and stay “young” throughout their lives.
fields.fact: Those sweet little smiles can quickly turn into vacuum cleaners when it’s time to eat. Axolotls suck in their prey, which includes crustaceans, mollusks, insect eggs and small fish.

fields.name: Fossa
fields.description: At first glance, a fossa looks like some kind of cat, monkey, or weasel. It has paws with claws like a cat, a long tail like a monkey, and round little ears like a weasel, so it's easy to be confused! Although it shares some adaptive similarities with cats, the fossa is closely related to the mongoose and civet.
fields.fact: Their scientific name means "hidden anus".

fields.name: Dugong
fields.description: Dugongs are cousins of manatees and share a similar plump appearance, but have a dolphin fluke-like tail. And unlike manatees, which use freshwater areas, the dugong is strictly a marine mammal. Commonly known as "sea cows," dugongs graze peacefully on sea grasses in shallow coastal waters of the Indian and western Pacific Oceans.
fields.fact: Dugongs are referred to as sea cows because they use their strong, cleft upper lips to graze on sea grasses they uproot from the seafloor.

fields.name: Markhor
fields.description: The markhor are native to the mountains of the Hindu Kush and are one of the most striking goat species because of their long spiral horns. In adult males, these can reach up to 1.6m long and in females up to 25cm.
fields.fact: Afghan puppet shows known as buz-baz use markhor marionettes.

fields.name: Gerenuk
fields.description: Long legs, long necks and large eyes distinguish gerenuks from other African antelope. Unlike many other four-legged herbivores these petite animals often dine balanced on their hind legs.  Using this adaptation, gerenuks can eat leaves from high on bushes and shrubs that almost no other animal can reach.
fields.fact: Gerenuks NEVER need to drink. All the moisture they need comes from the plants they consume.

fields.name: Okapi
fields.description: The Okapi is beautiful and unusual. With its white-and-black striped hindquarters and front legs, it looks like it must be related to zebras! But take a look at an okapi’s head, and you’ll notice a resemblance to giraffes. The okapi is indeed the only living relative of the giraffe.
fields.fact: The okapi is an iconic species for the DRC. It has been revered by the Congolese for centuries, particularly by the Mbuti pygmy communities, from whom its name originates. Today, the okapi is a national treasure and features on DRC’s banknotes as well as the logo of ICCN.

fields.name: Pink Fairy Armadillo
fields.description: Also known as the Pichiciego, the pink fairy armadillo is the smallest known species of armadillo. Unique adaptations like an aerodynamic body shape, smooth dorsal shell, and sharp claws mean this creature is able to completely bury itself in sand in a matter of seconds and then nagivate underground with ease.
fields.fact: Also known as ‘the sand swimmer’ because of how quickly and easily they can navigate underground.

fields.name: Armadillo Girdled Lizard
fields.description: Endemic to the Northern and Western Cape provinces of South Africa, this lizard is basically a tiny dragon. This resemblance is especially pronounced when they roll themselves up to protect themselves from danger—the behaviour that earned them their name.
fields.fact: Armadillo Girdled Lizards are one of the few lizard species who give birth to live young, and there is some evidence that the females may actually feed her young, which is even more uncommon.

fields.name: Streaked Tenrec
fields.description: Lowland streaked tenrecs are small insectivorous mammals from Madagascar that basically look like pokemon. Their snouts are long and pointed, while the coat exhibits spines. They are distinguished by two main features: the first is a rather long, black-colored nose and the other feature is a black-colored coat, displaying yellow stripes and bright yellow spine crests, located over the top of their head and acts as a mean of self-defense against predators.
fields.fact: The only mammal species, practicing stridulation - this is when an animal rubs together parts of its body to give out a sound. For example, when a baby tenrec loses its mother, it will rub its spines together, emitting a specific noise, which will help the young find its mother.

fields.name: Sunda Colugo
fields.description: The Sunda flying lemur or “colugo” does not belong to the prosimian group like true lemurs, but is in a zoological order of its own. Flying lemurs do not actually fly, but glide from one tree to the next, by means of the patagium, a membrane that stretches from their forelimbs to their tail. There is little information about their life span but the oldest known individual in captivity lived to 17.5 years old.
fields.fact: The Phillipine Eagle is focused specifically on hunting the Philippine colugo, which makes up 90% of its diet. This eagle is at risk of extinction, making the colugo important for its continued survival.

fields.name: Raccoon Dog
fields.description: The most extraordinary thing about raccoon dogs is that they are not related to raccoons at all. Despite having faces that look identical, these east Asian dogs, also known as Tanuki, are are most closely related to foxes. Raccoon dogs live in Europe and Asia.
fields.fact: Raccoon dogs have also been significant in Japanese folklore since ancient times. They are portrayed as mischievous and jolly and are famous for shape-shifting. Many Japanese homes have a small statue of one on their bookshelves.

fields.name: Barreleye
fields.description: Even in a world full of adaptations for seeing in near-total darkness, the barreleye fish stands out as one of the most bizarre. Two small indentations where eyes might normally appear on a fish are actually the barreleye’s olfactory organs, and its eyes are two glowing green orbs behind its face that gaze up towards the top of its head.
fields.fact: In 2009, MBARI researchers showed that the fish can rotate its eyes towards the front to see its food when eating. Before that, scientists believed that the barreleye’s gaze was fixed looking straight up.

fields.name: Matamata Turtle
fields.description: A fascinating species with a characterful look. Their most prominent features being the triangular head shape, 'snorkel' nose extension and apparent sleepy smile. They are efficient ambush predators, dining mainly on fish in the wild.
fields.fact: The mata mata's neck is longer than its vertebra. It's so long that the turtle can "snorkel," stretching its neck so its pointy proboscis can come up for air while it stays on the bottom of a stream.

fields.name: Vogelkop - Superb bird-of-paradise
fields.description: The Vogelkop superb bird-of-paradise, is endemic to the Bird's Head Peninsula in New Guinea (Vogelkop in Dutch). First described in 1930 by Ernst Mayr, it had been treated as a subspecies of the superb bird-of-paradise but was elevated to the status of a full species in 2018 based on its striking black plumage that its feathers absorb 99.95 percent of light and behavioural differences especially visible in the courting male.
fields.fact: The species has an unusually low population of females, and competition amongst males for mates is intensely fierce. This has led the species to have one of the most bizarre and elaborate courtship displays in the avian world.

fields.name: Satanic Leaf-Tailed Gecko
fields.description: The Satanic Leaf-Tailed Gecko's tail is flattened and has a leaf-like appearance. During daylight hours, this adaptation helps the gecko blend into its surroundings. At night it helps the gecko hunt for prey by providing camouflage.
fields.fact: Geckos possess no eyelids but just a transparent covering over their eyes. So to wipe away any dust or debris that gets into their eyes they use their long, mobile tongues.

fields.name: Yeti Crab
fields.description: Kiwa are a genus of marine decapods that inhabit hydrothermal vents and cold seeps at deep-sea levels. They have three nicknames that are often used instead of their actual name – yeti crab, yeti lobster, or furry lobster.
fields.fact: The yeti crab farms its own food – on its arms.

fields.name: Goblin Shark
fields.description: The very strange-looking Goblin Shark has a distinctively shaped snout and an impressive array of long, pointed teeth. The fish, however, is luckily found in deep water and poses no threat to people.
fields.fact: Though close to the head in this picture, it can be extended to the length of its snout to help the goblin shark ambush fish, squids and crustaceans...

fields.name: Long-wattled Umbrellabird
fields.description: Spectacular crow-like bird with a bushy crest. Male has a thick feathered wattle dangling from his throat that can be extended to an astonishing length while displaying. It inhabits tall, lush, and undisturbed rainforest in western Ecuador and western Colombia. Quite scarce, and usually encountered at fruiting trees or at known display sites, where several males may congregate, extending their wattles and giving very low-pitched, airy hoots.
fields.fact: Monkeys and snakes are the primarily predators of the umbrellabird, along with large birds of prey such as hawks and eagles.

fields.name: Cantor's Giant Softshell Turtle
fields.description: Cantor’s giant softshell is an exceptionally large freshwater turtle, with individuals known to reach over 1 metre in length and weigh more than 100 kilograms! Sadly, these extraordinary turtles are on the brink of extinction.
fields.fact: Cantor's giant turtles spend most of their life buried and motionless, with only their eyes and mouth protruding from the sand.

fields.name: Japanese Spider Crab
fields.description: They may look like something from a 1950's sci-fi film, but Japanese Spider Crab's are gentle giants. A spider crab travels easily over the mud on long limber legs. This seafloor scavenger is quick to lunch on leftover scraps or dead animals that fall from above.
fields.fact: Due to their length and spiny attachments, the legs of Japanese spider crabs may get torn off when caught in fishing nets or by predators. These limbs can regrow when the crab goes through a molting cycle

fields.name: Giant Hornless Rhino
fields.description: Paraceratherium is an extinct genus of hornless rhinoceros. It is one of the largest terrestrial mammals that has ever existed. The first fossils were discovered in what is now Pakistan, and remains have been found across Eurasia between China and the Balkans.
fields.fact: The Giant Rhino is as tall as the modern day Giraffe and as heavy as four modern African Elephants.

fields.name: Giant Sloth
fields.description: Giant ground sloths were large, lumbering beasts that lived in the Americas during the Ice Age. They were directly related to today's modern sloths. They were also distantly related to anteaters and armadillos.
fields.fact: There is new evidence to suggest that although Giant Sloths were largely herbivorous, they may have the scavenged left-overs of predators.

fields.name: Giant Dragonfly
fields.description: Meganeura is a genus of extinct insects from the Carboniferous period , which resembled and are related to the present-day dragonflies. Its wingspans from 65 cm (25.6 in) to more than 70 cm (28 in).  Meganeura was predatory and their diet consisted mainly of other insects
fields.fact: The Giant Dragonfly ruled the skies before pterosaurs, birds and bats had even evolved.

fields.name: Giant Pacarana
fields.description: Josephoartigasia is an extinct genus of giant rodent from the Early to Late Pliocene related to the living pacarana. The genus includes the largest known rodent, Josephoartigasia monesi. The two species would have resembled gigantic pacarana, or capybaras the size of cows.
fields.fact: It is thought that the Giant Pacarana used its front teeth as tusks for digging in the ground for food or defending itself from predators.

fields.name: Giant Beaver
fields.description: As its common name implies, the giant beaver looked generally similar to the modern beaver, but was considerably larger. By comparison, however, its hind feet were greatly enlarged. It is uncertain as to whether the tail was similar to that of the modern beaver (broad and flattened, like a paddle), because the tails are made of soft tissue, which decays and disappears. For this same reason, we can only assume that its feet were also webbed.
fields.fact: The Giant Beaver weighed the same as a Black Bear.

fields.name: Giant Alligator
fields.description: The snout of Deinosuchus resembles a modern day alligator with robust teeth that could crunch bone.‭ ‬These teeth combined with a powerful bites force measured in tons point towards a specialisation in hunting large and possibly armoured animals.‭
fields.fact: It is thought that the Giant Alligator's jaw was so strong that it must have hunted dinosaurs.

fields.name: Giant Turtle
fields.description: Archelon was a slow mover and found most of its food drifting near the sea surface. It had little need to dive deep except when hibernating on the seabed. It was an omnivorous grazer, sweeping up drifting fish, jellyfish and dead carrion as well as plants. Its sharp, powerful beak could break open shelled animals such as ammonites.
fields.fact: Like modern turtles, it laid eggs by burying them in sandy beaches under cover of darkness. Its nearest living relative is the world's largest turtle, the leatherback.

fields.name: Giant Snake
fields.description: The giant snake lived during the Middle to Late Paleocene epoch, a 10-million-year period immediately following the Cretaceous-Paleogene extinction event. The only known species is Titanoboa cerrejonensis, the largest snake ever discovered, which supplanted the previous record holder, Gigantophis.
fields.fact: The snake's enormous size is thought to have been possible due to the particularly warm climate. Also, it the Titanboa may have eaten crocodiles.

fields.name: Giant Shark
fields.description: Considered to be the largest shark, as well as the largest fish, that ever lived. Estimates suggest it grew to between 15 and 18 metres in length, three times longer than the largest recorded great white shark. Despite what the Discovery Channel (and Jason Statham) might say, sadly the Megladon is definitely extinct.
fields.fact: It is thought that the Meg went extinct because of competition with the modern day Great White.
